diff:1616909529:1616909529:=1,76d0%0a%3c :Category: PhonologicalPhenomenaInSpokenLanguages%0a%3c :Essential: {Category.PhonologicalPhenomenaInSpokenLanguages$:essential}%0a%3c :Title: Schwa deletion in Indian Languages %0a%3c :Author: Mihir_D%0a%3c :Section: A%0a%3c :Completed: 27.03.2021 - 22:32%0a%3c :Status: ungraded%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#history]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#historyend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c %25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#comments]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#commentsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c !!%0a%3c %0a%3c Summary: \\%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summary]]%0a%3c %0a%3c Different Indian languages have a phenomena of deleting schwas that would have been present%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summaryends]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c [[#content]]%0a%3c %0a%3c Many Indian languages belong to the Indo-Aryan branch of the Indo-European language family, with the modern languages descending partly from Sanskrit. Some of these languages feature the phenomenon of schwa deletion, where an implicit schwa (pronounced as /ə/ or /ɐ/) present in the Sanskrit root word and written script is not pronounced. An example language that heavily features this phenomenon is Hindi. A language that features only some aspects of schwa deletion is Marathi. %0a%3c %0a%3c The a religious text "Veda" is spelled as वेद in Hindi, Marathi, and Sanskrit, but is pronounced differently:%0a%3c Sanskrit: [ʋedɐ]%0a%3c Marathi: [ʋed]  (deleted schwa)%0a%3c Hindi: [ʋed]    (deleted schwa)%0a%3c %0a%3c Word final schwas seem to be deleted more often than medial ones in languages such as Marathi. Hindi tends delete schwas about 89%25 of the time when in an environment like VC_CV. %0a%3c %0a%3c The word रचना has the same spelling and meaning in all 3 languages, but has different pronunciations: %0a%3c Sanskrit: [rətʃənaː]%0a%3c Marathi: [rətʃənaː]%0a%3c Hindi: [rətʃnaː] (2nd schwa deleted)%0a%3c %0a%3c In the US, many people debated how to pronounce Vice President Kamala Harris' first name, and part of the problem comes with Schwa deletion. In Hindi it would be pronounced [kəmlɐ]. But in Sanskrit or Tamil (her mother's native language) it is [kəməlɐ]. Her official pronunciation is based on this second form [kɑːmələ].%0a%3c %0a%3c Interestingly, the phenomenon seems to be changing Marathi. Due to high contact with languages such as Hindi, there has been an increase of schwa deletion in Marathi as well. I have seen this change in my own family, who all speak the language.%0a%3c %0a%3c The words गुण and गोड were pronounced as [guɳə] and [goɖə] by people in my great-grandparents' generation and are pronounced as [guɳ] and [goɖ] now. The road my grandparents live on has the word मार्ग in its name. This is pronounced as [maɾɡə] by my grandparents, but more like [maɾɡ] (as it is in Hindi) by their younger neighbors. %0a%3c %0a%3c One possible reason for this phenomenon is talking quickly. English (another Indo-European language) seems to feature some schwa deletion today as well. In these examples, the schwa before a stressless syllable is deleted if the word is said too quickly or in a sentence. %0a%3c %0a%3c Opera: [ɑpəɹə] -> [ɑpɹə]%0a%3c General:[d͡ʒɛnəɹəl] -> [d͡ʒɛnɹəl%0a%3c Chocolate: [t͡ʃɔkəlɪt] -> [t͡ʃɔklɪt]%0a%3c %0a%3c In English schwa deletion does not occur word initially or finally, but may occur in the middle of a word.%0a%3c %0a%3c Sources: %0a%3c http://www.aellk.or.kr/datax/thesis/1613433509823.pdf%0a%3c https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schwa_deletion_in_Indo-Aryan_languages%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
